# Line-break / word-wrapping policy

On EVERY page (desktop and mobile), text must never break in the middle of a
word. Lines wrap at semantic boundaries, while staying visually clean.

## Rules

- Never split a word mid-character. Do NOT use `overflow-wrap: break-word`,
  `overflow-wrap: anywhere`, `word-break: break-all`, or `word-break: break-word`
  on text content (headings, paragraphs, list items, links, buttons, labels).
- Latin text (English / French) wraps only at spaces → use
  `overflow-wrap: normal; word-break: normal;`.
- Chinese wraps between characters (that is its correct semantic behaviour) — the
  default `word-break: normal` already handles this; do not force `keep-all`.
- Disable hyphenation: `hyphens: none; -webkit-hyphens: none;` so words are never
  broken with a hyphen.
- For aesthetics, prefer `text-wrap: balance` on headings and `text-wrap: pretty`
  on body copy.
- To prevent long words from overflowing on narrow screens, REDUCE font size via
  responsive `clamp()` / media queries — never by breaking the word.

## Example

```css
/* GOOD */
h1, h2, h3, p, li, a {
  overflow-wrap: normal;
  word-break: normal;
  hyphens: none;
}
h1, h2, h3 { text-wrap: balance; }

/* BAD — splits words mid-character */
h1 { overflow-wrap: break-word; }
```
